etymologies: late 15th century; earliest use found in Acts of Lords of Council in Civil Causes. From sub- + vassal [adjective]

definitions: A person who holds land as the vassal of a person who himself or herself holds the land as a vassal, in later use usually in return for the annual payment of feu duty. Compare "undervassal", and earlier "subvavasour".

notes.text: The Scottish vassalage system was abolished in 2000 by the Abolition of Feudal Tenure (Scotland) Act.
